1440":"1384–1440","1369–Female":"1369–Deceased","1369":"1369","1455":"1455","1440":"1440","1341":"1341","1384":"1384","1382":"1382","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, Inglaterra, Reino Unido":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","York, Yorkshire, Inglaterra":"York, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"señora","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of Polish, Jewish (from Poland), Czech, Slovak, and Rusyn (from Slovakia)   Sikora   and Czech, Slovak, and Rusyn (from Slovakia) <b>Sýkora</b> (see   Sykora  ), all meaning ‘tit(mouse)’ or ‘coalmouse’. Compare   Secor   and   Secore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sikora","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jozef, Zbigniew, Zdzislaw, Andrzej, Casimir, Jadwiga, Janina, Janusz, Katarzyna, Kazimierz, Miroslaw, Piotr.","Polish and Jewish (from Poland): from Polish <i>sikora</i> ‘titmouse, coalmouse’, hence a nickname for a small, dark person, or, in the case of the Jewish name, an artificial name.","Jewish (from Poland): habitational name from any of the villages called Sikory."]}]},{"name":"Whitton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Whitton in Morebattle (Roxburghshire). The placename is from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farm, village’, as with many of the places in 2 below.","English: habitational name from any of the places called Whitton (Durham, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Northumberland, Shropshire, Suffolk) or Witton (Cheshire, Durham, Lancashire, Herefordshire, Norfolk, Northumberland, Warwickshire, Worcestershire, North Yorkshire); or possibly from Wyton (Huntingdonshire, East Yorkshire); or possibly from Weeton, Market Weighton, or Little Weighton (East Yorkshire). The placenames do not all share the same etymology but most of their post-medieval spellings are interchangeable. Most of the placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> or Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some, for example Witton in Warwickshire, derive from Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farmstead’ + <i>tūn</i>, and some others, for example Witton in Norfolk, derive from Old English <i>widu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>tūn</i>. Whitton in Lincolnshire derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> (genitive <i>Hwītan</i>) or Old English <i>hwīt</i> (dative <i>hwītan</i>) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. Witton in Lancashire derives from the Old English personal <i>Witta</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","English: in Devon, this surname is a variant of   Whiddon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Whitten","meanings":["English: variant of   Whitton   or   Whiting  ."]},{"name":"Whetten","meanings":["English, Scottish, or northern Irish: variant of   Whitton  ."]},{"name":"Whiddon","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from any of numerous minor places in Devon named Whiddon. Some are named with Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ or <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’; others with Old English <i>hwǣte</i> ‘wheat’ + <i>dūn</i> or <i>denu</i> ‘valley’."]},{"name":"Whiton","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of   Whitton  . This surname is now rare in Britain.","History: James Whiton of Hingham, Norfolk, England, came to Plymouth, MA, in 1635."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":13,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":86,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","descripti